# Architectural Constraints

## app.js vs index.js — never merge them

`app.js` exports the Express app for testing. `index.js` is the server entry point.

```js
// ✅ app.js — testable, no side effects
import express from 'express'
const app = express()
// ... routes ...
export default app

// ✅ index.js — server entry only
import app from './app.js'
app.listen(process.env.PORT || 8080)
```

- Never call `app.listen()` inside `app.js`
- Never import routes or middleware directly in `index.js` — that's `app.js`'s job
- Tests always import from `app.js`, never from `index.js`

## Middleware placement

Auth middleware belongs in `middleware/` and is applied per-route, not globally.

```js
// ✅ GOOD — scoped to the route that needs it
app.post('/contact', authMiddleware, handler)

// ❌ BAD — applies auth to all routes including GET /
app.use(authMiddleware)
```

## Module boundaries

- One concern per file: `middleware/auth.js` handles auth only
- No business logic in middleware — validate the token, call `next()` or return 401, nothing else
- Route handlers do not import `jsonwebtoken` directly — that's the middleware's job
